Actually, I have to say, I think not, and I have a very, very good reason for thinking so.

See, Amber NEVER succeeded in any of her attempts to take legal actions against Johnny apart from her BS restraining order, which frankly means she didn't actually do any real harm to him directly, not even using the courts as her proxy as she tried.

Yet, still, she managed to do tens of millions of dollars worth in damages anyway. How did she do this? Through the court of public opinion. She stirred the pot with lies and deception, and the public responded, burying Depp's gig on Pirates of the Caribbean in the process.

Yes, it might be cathartic seeing her get fired, but at the end of the day, it pails in comparison because that job is worth a fraction of the one she cost Johnny, and even if the two were comparable, it just brings us full circle, right back to the root of the problem, and that problem is COURTS SHOULD BE AJUDICATING CRIMINAL TRIALS, NOT HR DEPARTMENTS.

If we didn't have a culture that was so damn happy to see people fired over meer accusations in the first place, she could have never done the degree of damage she did.

By celebrating her being fired, we are just perpetuating the problem that started it all, and no, there is no reason to celebrate her being fired. Why? Because if she goes to prison for her crimes, her employment gets rendered a moot issue anyway.

In fact, I wish she had not been fired. If she loses her job, I would hope it would be because she was too busy sitting handcuffed in a prison cell to work, not because some busy body decided the accusations against her were a bad fit for the company.

That's how it SHOULD BE, and if it was that way when it was Johnny on the chopping block, we would have had a much better outcome all around.

Quit trying to turn HR into a court of law.
